                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d847">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/8–945: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hurley</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-08-09T11:00:00+07:00"
                            >August 9, 1945—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 4 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1312. Secretary of the Treasury, Washington, from Adler.<note n="9"
                        xml:id="d847fn9">Presumably in further answer to Department’s telegram No.
                        761, May 20, 1 p.m., <ref target="#pg_1096">p. 1096</ref>.</note> Ambassador
                    Hurley informs me that he is strongly in favor of China’s setting up a U. S.
                    dollar half-billion currency stabilization fund, provided that fund is
                    constituted from China’s existing dollar assets. He is definitely of opinion,
                    and has told T. V. Soong, that American voice and advice should be heard in
                    management of fund. Ambassador Hurley has also discussed fund with
                    Generalissimo. [Adler.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hurley</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
